To install esphome, do this:

First a word on environements. This requires python, a recommended solution to deal with python versions is to use pyenv.
See here for how to setup pyenv: https://opensource.com/article/19/5/python-3-default-mac

git clone https://github.com/esphome/esphome.git
cd esphome && git checkout dev
./script/setup

To activate the python virtual environment in a terminal shell,
do this:

source venv/bin/activate

Now after cd-ing into the growOS/esphome directory, either
source .bashrc or append it's contents into your !/.bashrc.

Now it is possible to build and run esphome for CPU 0 like this:

To generate the yaml for, just run make for CPU0 or make1 for CPU1.

compile
upload
logs

To build for CPU1, pass PROJTAG=1 to your make command. Or use the alias
make1.

The Makefile chooses a board serial number and network location
based on $USER and generates a full yaml file for esphome.
For now, only two userids (erik and maarten) are supported.
The files location.pec and location.sxm have that localization.

Once the yaml files are generated, instead of driving things
from the Makefile, it is also possible to issue esphome commands
directly on the generated yaml file, such as:

esphome compile proj.0.yaml
esphome upload proj.0.yaml
esphome logs proj.0.yaml

See esphome -h for more details.

aliases for the above are in ./Bashrc.  Source it or add it to your !/.bashrc.

There are some intermediate C-preprocessed files stored in
./proj.0 and ./proj.1

It is possible to connect to the growboard's IP address
from a browser to see some published information and flip
some switches.

Voila!


Notes:
On first upload without existing esphome firmware, will have to program over serial
/dev/* will be the path of the serial port, which can be found by looking at the output of dmesg after plugging in the growboard
Sometimes the "cu." needs to be added for paths such as /dev/usbserial-A50285BI

